<br>
AF jobs that translate well to civilian careers ... I have seen about 3 so far ... I'm sure there's more.<br>
<br>
The recruiter is going to push Security Forces on you.  He/She has a lot of quotas to fill there.  The guys I knew in SF all get out after 4 years for jobs in law enforcement.  It's practically a sure thing that a job as a cop is waiting for you if you keep a clean record.  The SF guys I knew were happy with it for the most part, and there's some comraderie there, that I have seen.  My personal advice to you is only take this option if you're interested in a law enforcement career.  The hours you work are long, odd hours, and alot of the time you'll be bored on watch.  If it's something you're not interested in, you won't be very happy.  Remember, when the recruiter pushes this on you, you don't have to take it.<br>
<br>
I'm a 3COX1 (Computer Operator), and I do Network Architecture, Systems Administration, Web Development (and more) ... Eventually, I'll probably have all the skills I need for an MSE certification.  I work steady hours, and have time for college courses.  I've seen a few guys get out after 4 years to take jobs at places like Compaq doing Sys Admin work on Web Servers.  We're a critical field, high enlistment/reenlistment bonuses.  I really like/recommend this field, and I'd suggest holding out for it.  I had to wait 3 months from the time I approached the  recruiter til the time I shipped out to get it.  Hold out for the career you want ... don't settle, and don't go open/general.<br>
<br>
I've seen that Air Traffic Control was another good job that has a civilian career waiting, as well.<br>
<br>
Oh, you can also go into Medical ... and have a career that translates well into medical administration, nursing, dental assistant ... or with your degree, anything you want in the medical world.<br>
<br>
Speaking of jobs, if I don't get going now, I'll be late getting to post.<br>
<br>
Best of luck,<br>
